sec.p:
Koelreuteria , usually used as popular ornamental trees, comprises three extant species in eastern Asia and its distribution spans temperate and subtropical regions (
Wu et al. , 2007
;
Acevedo-Rodríguez et al. , 2010
). Koelreuteria paniculata Laxm.
is widely distributed in temperate areas of eastern Asia ( China , Japan , and Korea ), K. bipinnata Franch.
is found mainly in subtropical areas of southern and southwestern China , while K. elegans subsp. formosana is restricted to Taiwan island, China ( Xia & Luo, 1995 ). It has long been recognized that climatic conditions plays an important role in reproductive isolation and speciation ( Sutherst & Yonow, 1998 ;
Lange et al. , 2006
;
Sosa-Pivatto et al. , 2020
). The geographical distributions of the aphid P. koelreuteriae and Koelreuteria host plants are relatively similar in mainland China (
Wang et al. , 1991
; Xia & Luo, 1995 ;
Liu et al. , 1999
;
Wang et al. , 2013
; Junkiert & Wieczorek, 2019 ). Our previous studies based on DNA barcodes and integrative data have shown that P. koelreuteriae should be a species complex containing previously unknown lineages and climate and host plant may have driven the differentiation of three close species (
Li et al. , 2020
;
Li et al. , 2021
). These unrevealed lineages represent two new species from subtropical highland areas and subtropical humid areas, respectively. The main purpose of this study is to further validate the two new species and describe in detail the morphological diagnoses of them, based on apterous viviparous females and alate viviparous females.

Molecular data and analyses. We extracted the whole genomic DNA of each sample from a single individual preserved in ethanol using the DNeasy Blood &Tissue Kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany ). The barcoding region of COI (the mitochondrial cytochrome c oxidase subunit I) was amplified using the following primers: COI LepF ATTCAACCAATCATAAAGATATTGG and COI LepR TAAACTTCTGGATGTCCAAAAAATCA (
Foottit et al. , 2008
). The polymerase chain reaction (PCR) was performed using a 25 μL reaction volume with the mixture of 1 μL template DNA, 0.5 μL forward and reverse primer (10 μm), 0.25 μL Taq DNA polymerase (5 U/μL), 18.25 μL double distilled H 2 O, 2.5 μL 10× buffer and 2 μL dNTP. The COI gene fragment amplification was carried out with the following conditions: 5 min of initial denaturation at 95°C, 35 cycles of 20s at 94°C, 30s at 54°C (the annealing temperature) and 72 °C at 2 min, and 10 min of final extension at 72°C. The products of PCR were run in 1% agarose gels and bidirectionally sequenced at Sangon Biotech ( Shanghai , China ).

